As part of the migration, there were some components added to the AWS account. Team created one of the EC2 instances where they need to make some changes now.

There is an EC2 instance named devops-ec2 under us-east-1 region, enable the stop protection for this instance.

Steps Using AWS Console:
1. Login to AWS Console:
Go to the AWS Management Console.
Log in with your credentials.
2. Navigate to EC2 Service:
In the search bar at the top, type EC2 and select EC2 from the list of services.
3. Locate the Instance:
In the EC2 dashboard, select Instances from the left-hand side.
In the us-east-1 region, find the devops-ec2 instance in the list of EC2 instances.
4. Enable Stop Protection:
Select the devops-ec2 instance by clicking the checkbox next to the instance.
From the Actions dropdown, choose Instance Settings > Change Termination Protection.
In the Change Termination Protection window, select Enable to enable the stop protection for the instance.
Click Apply.
5. Confirm Protection:
After enabling stop protection, you will see a Termination Protection label in the Description tab of the instance with the value set to Enabled.

Steps Using AWS CLI:
1. Enable Stop Protection for the Instance:
To enable stop protection for the EC2 instance devops-ec2, run the following AWS CLI command:
aws ec2 modify-instance-attribute --instance-id i-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx --no-disable-api-termination --region us-east-1

2. Verify Termination Protection:
After enabling stop protection, you can verify the status with the following command:

aws ec2 describe-instances --instance-ids i-xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx --query 'Reservations[0].Instances[0].DisableApiTermination'

